 regime, which defined the racial categories that continue to influence perceptions in the United States about Mexican Americans, race, and ethnicity. Molina demonstrates that despite the multiplicity of influences that help shape our concept of race, common themes prevail. Examining legal, political, social, and cultural sources related to immigration, she advances the theory that our understanding of race is socially constructed in relational ways—that is, in correspondence to other groups. Molina introduces and explains her central theory, racial scripts, which highlights the ways in which the lives of racialized groups are linked across time and space and thereby affect one another. How Race Is Made in America also shows that these racial scripts are easily adopted and adapted to apply to different racial groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCitizenshipzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDeportationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericansxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aRace discriminationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a20th century american history.  aamerican crossroads series.  aamerican history.  aamerican immigration.  aamerican laws.  aamerican studies.  abirthright citizenship.  adeportation.  aethnicity.  ahistorical.  aimmigrants.  aimmigration law.  aimmigration regime.  aimmigration.  aimmigraton policy.  alegislation.  amedical racialization.  amexican americans.  arace and citizenship.  arace in america.  arace.  aracial categories.  aracial scripts.  aracialized groups.  areduced immigration.  asocial construction of race.  aunited states of a